04655nam a22007335i 9780231537766DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013040700  a97802315377667 a10.7312/chak165962doi  a(DE-B1597)458273  a(OCoLC)979739582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPK5416b.C43 2014 4aPK5416b.C43 2017 7aLIT0080202bisacsh04a891.42231 aChakravorty, Mrinalini, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Stereotype :bSouth Asia in the Global Literary Imaginary /cMrinalini Chakravorty. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b6 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature Now00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: Stereotypes as Provocation -- t1. Why the Stereotype? Why South Asia? -- t2. To Understand Me, You’ll Have to Swallow a World -- t3. Slumdog or White Tiger? -- t4. The Dead That Haunt Anil’s Ghost -- t5. From Bangladesh to Brick Lane -- t6. Good and Bad Transnationalisms? -- tEpilogue: The Afterlife of Stereotypes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Stereotype confronts the importance of cultural stereotypes in shaping the ethics and reach of global literature. Mrinalini Chakravorty focuses on the seductive force and explanatory power of stereotypes in multiple South Asian contexts, whether depicting hunger, crowdedness, filth, slums, death, migrant flight, terror, or outsourcing. She argues that such commonplaces are crucial to defining cultural identity in contemporary literature and shows how the stereotype's ambivalent nature exposes the crises of liberal development in South Asia.In Stereotype considers the influential work of Salman Rushdie, Aravind Adiga, Michael Ondaatje, Monica Ali, Mohsin Hamid, and Chetan Bhagat, among others, to illustrate how stereotypes about South Asia provide insight into the material and psychic investments of contemporary imaginative texts: the colonial novel, the transnational film, and the international best-seller. Probing circumstances that range from the independence of the Indian subcontinent to poverty tourism, civil war, migration, domestic labor, and terrorist radicalism, Chakravorty builds an interpretive lens for reading literary representations of cultural and global difference. In the process, she also reevaluates the fascination with transnational novels and films that manufacture global differences by staging intersubjective encounters between cultures through stereotypes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSouth Asian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSouth Asian literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Indic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chak1659640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231537766.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK